    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-07-29T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-07-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="665"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d665">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 PW/7–2948</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Statement by the United States Representative on the Far
                        Eastern Commission</hi> (<hi rend="italic">McCoy</hi>) <hi rend="italic">on
                            <gloss target="#t_FEC1">FEC</gloss>–011/51 at 117th <gloss
                            target="#t_FEC1">FEC</gloss> Meeting, 29 July 1948</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d665fn1">Copy transmitted to the Department by the Secretary
                        General of the <gloss target="#t_FEC1">FEC</gloss> on July 29. Mr. Johnson
                        stated that the Soviet Representative abstained from voting on <gloss
                            target="#t_FEC1">FEC</gloss>–011/51, July 29; for text of latter, see
                            <hi rend="italic">The Far Eastern Commission</hi>, 2d report, p.
                        37.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-head" calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1948-07-29">July 29, 1948</date>
                </dateline>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_SCAP1">SCAP</gloss> has advised the United States Government
                    that upon examination of stocks of gold and silver now in Japan and pertinent
                    records, he has made a determination that certain gold and silver is of clearly
                    established Japanese ownership. He has placed this gold and silver in accordance
                    with the terms of <gloss target="#t_FEC1">FEC</gloss>–032/26, para. 16<hi
                        rend="italic">c</hi>
                    <note n="2" xml:id="d665fn2">July 24, 1947, <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, pp.
                        31, 33.</note> in a fund created as a means of acquiring foreign exchange to
                    aid in financing Japanese production programs. The United States Government has
                    reviewed and considers proper <gloss target="#t_SCAP1">SCAP’s</gloss> finding
                    and action in this matter. It is therefore the viewpoint of the United States
                    Government that the provisions of <gloss target="#t_FEC1">FEC</gloss>–011/51,
                    which deal with restitution of looted property found in Japan, will not affect
                    in any way this gold and silver which <gloss target="#t_SCAP1">SCAP</gloss> has
                    determined to be Japanese owned, or any gold and silver which <gloss
                        target="#t_SCAP1">SCAP</gloss> may in the future in accordance with the
                    terms of <gloss target="#t_FEC1">FEC</gloss>–011/51 find to be Japanese owned,
                    or the use of such gold and silver in connection with credits under the terms of
                        <gloss target="#t_FEC1">FEC</gloss>–032/26, para. 16<hi rend="italic"
                        >c</hi>.<note n="3" xml:id="d665fn3">
                        <gloss target="#t_FEC1">FEC</gloss>–011/51 was sent as directive serial 93
                        to <gloss target="#t_SCAP1">SCAP</gloss>. (740.00119 PW/8–1348)</note>
                </p>
            </div>
